About

Genius Annotation

“Party in the U.S.A.” was co-written by English singer-songwriter Jessie J; she originally intended to sing it (listen to the leaked snippet of the demo version), but decided to pass the song over to Miley after concluding that it didn’t fit her persona:

That was my first week of writing after I signed to (Universal) Republic (Records), so it was like the first big kind of writing session for my debut album … and it was one of the first songs we did. And I remember thinking this song is amazing, but I don’t know if it’s me 110 percent, you know. You can kind of feel it. It was cool but it wasn’t edgy enough.

Q&A

Find answers to frequently asked questions about the song and explore its deeper meaning

What did Miley Cyrus say about "Party in the U.S.A."?
Genius Answer

Cyrus has stated “Party in the U.S.A.” is not a reflection of her musically, as she preferred songs with more of an edge. She said the track was “an all-American song” and claimed she had never heard a Jay-Z song in November 2009, an artist which the lyrics refer to.

How did the song perform commercially?
Genius Answer

The song peaked at #2 in the United States, #3 in New Zealand, #6 in France, #6 in Australia, #11 in the United Kingdom, and #23 in Denmark. More worldwide chart positions are available through achart.co.

According to Billboard, the song re-entered the Hot 100 chart after thirteen years after it’s first appearance in 2010, at #50 during the tracking week ending July 15, 2023, due to “annual Fourth of July gains.”

Did this song receive any certifications?
Genius Answer

Yes! This song was certified Diamond by the RIAA on December 7, 2020.
